\textbf{(SINR $\approx$ SNR) validation}. Fig. \ref{fig:SINR_SNR} shows simulation results for the CCDF of the mmWave UEs UL and DL $\mathtt{SINR}$ and $\mathtt{SNR}$ for two different mmWave Scells densities. It can be seen from the figure that for $\lambda_s = 30/\mathrm{km^2}$ the $\mathtt{SINR}$ and $\mathtt{SNR}$ are almost overlapping and even at $\lambda_s = 200/\mathrm{km^2}$ the difference between $\mathtt{SINR}$ and $\mathtt{SNR}$ is very small. This result confirms our assumption that interference in mmWave has a minimal impact on coverage for the mmWave Scells densities considered in our scenario. This, in turn, confirms that the $\mathtt{SINR}$ can be approximated by the $\mathtt{SNR}$ for mmWaves which is quite different than the trend in sub-6GHz networks where $\mathtt{SINR} \approx \mathtt{SIR}$. Furthermore, the break point in the curves at 30\% and 90\% of the CCDF for $\lambda_s$ of 30 and 200 shows how the $\mathtt{SNR}$ starts degrading quickly after a certain point which is a result of the LOS ball blockage model which assumes that beyond a certain distance between the UE and the BSs all the UEs are considered non line of sight. In addition, the degradation affects fewer UEs at $\lambda_s = 200/\mathrm{km^2}$ since at a higher density fewer UEs are expected to be outside the LOS ball of the mmWave Scells.

